column12: The epitope is a peptide-like structure where the D-Glutamic acid residues are linked in amide bonds between the amino group and the gamma-carboxyl group instead of the alpha-carboxyl. The B.anthracis capsule antigen is a polymer of D-glutamic acid residues where the peptide bond is made via the gamma-carboxyl group. It is enzymatically synthesized.
This epitope is a nonamer consisting of D-glutamic acid residues linked at the gamma-COOH groups.  It is derived from the capsule of Bacillus anthracis, which is a polymer of gamma-D-glutamic acid.
This epitope is a decamer consisting of D-glutamic acid residues linked at the COOH groups. It is derived from the capsule of Bacillus anthracis, which is a polymer of D-glutamic acid.

column12: The structure depicted corresponds to 2-O-methyl-4-(3-hydroxy-3-methylbutamido)-4,6-dideoxy-beta-d-glucopyranosyl-(1→3)-alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1→3)-alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl, which is part of the O-linked oligosaccharide subsitutuent of the glycoportein BclA found in B. anthracis exosporium. The non-reducing sugar, 2-O-methyl-4-(3-hydroxy-3-methylbutamido)-4,6-dideoxy-beta-d-glucopyranose, is a previously unknown saccharide found in B. anthracis and therefore called anthrose. The BclA (collagen-like) glycoprotein is found in B. anthracis exosporium, and it has a repeating region of X-X-Gly motif, which usually has a Thr residue that is a potential glycosylation site. The glycoprotein oligosaccharide moiety is studied here.
The author-cited GenBank source for the epitope sequence lists a "D" residue in the C-terminal position, while the authors list a "T" residue in the table.
The epitope sequence was deduced.
